rename.to: [BUG] Internal Server Error while launching the MLFlow UI

body:
More analysis and observation - 
The query works fine if I replace all the values in the statement as such - 
```
declare @p1 int
set @p1=NULL
exec sp_prepexec @p1 output,N'@P1 int,@P2 int,@P3 nvarchar(2),@P4 nvarchar(12),@P5 int,@P6 int,@P7 int,@P8 int',
N'SELECT DISTINCT runs.run_uuid AS runs_run_uuid, runs.name AS runs_name, runs.source_type AS runs_source_type, 
runs.source_name AS runs_source_name, runs.entry_point_name AS runs_entry_point_name, runs.user_id AS runs_user_id, 
runs.status AS runs_status, runs.start_time AS runs_start_time, runs.end_time AS runs_end_time, 
runs.source_version AS runs_source_version, runs.lifecycle_stage AS runs_lifecycle_stage, runs.artifact_uri AS runs_artifact_uri, 
runs.experiment_id AS runs_experiment_id, CASE WHEN (runs.start_time IS NULL) THEN 1 ELSE 0 END AS anon_1 
FROM runs 
WHERE runs.experiment_id IN (N''0'') AND runs.lifecycle_stage IN (N''active'') 
ORDER BY CASE WHEN (runs.start_time IS NULL) THEN 1 ELSE 0 END, runs.start_time DESC, runs.run_uuid
 OFFSET 0 ROWS
 FETCH FIRST 100 ROWS ONLY', 1, 0, N'0',N'active',1, 0, 0,100
 select @p1
```
Now, if I replace only the variables inside the **case** statement with the actual value and let the other variables remain as it is, then too the sql statement works - 

```

declare @p1 int
set @p1=NULL
exec sp_prepexec @p1 output,N'@P1 int,@P2 int,@P3 nvarchar(2),@P4 nvarchar(12),@P5 int,@P6 int,@P7 int,@P8 int',
N'SELECT DISTINCT runs.run_uuid AS runs_run_uuid, runs.name AS runs_name, runs.source_type AS runs_source_type, 
runs.source_name AS runs_source_name, runs.entry_point_name AS runs_entry_point_name, runs.user_id AS runs_user_id, 
runs.status AS runs_status, runs.start_time AS runs_start_time, runs.end_time AS runs_end_time, 
runs.source_version AS runs_source_version, runs.lifecycle_stage AS runs_lifecycle_stage, runs.artifact_uri AS runs_artifact_uri, 
runs.experiment_id AS runs_experiment_id, CASE WHEN (runs.start_time IS NULL) THEN 1 ELSE 0 END AS anon_1 
FROM runs 
WHERE runs.experiment_id IN (@P3) AND runs.lifecycle_stage IN (@P4) 
ORDER BY CASE WHEN (runs.start_time IS NULL) THEN 1 ELSE 0 END, runs.start_time DESC, runs.run_uuid
 OFFSET @P7 ROWS
 FETCH FIRST @P8 ROWS ONLY',1,0,N'0',N'active',1,0,0,100
select @p1
```
However, If the variables in side the **case** statement are not replace, the query starts to break again - 

```

declare @p1 int
set @p1=NULL
exec sp_prepexec @p1 output,N'@P1 int,@P2 int,@P3 nvarchar(2),@P4 nvarchar(12),@P5 int,@P6 int,@P7 int,@P8 int',
N'SELECT DISTINCT runs.run_uuid AS runs_run_uuid, runs.name AS runs_name, runs.source_type AS runs_source_type, 
runs.source_name AS runs_source_name, runs.entry_point_name AS runs_entry_point_name, runs.user_id AS runs_user_id, 
runs.status AS runs_status, runs.start_time AS runs_start_time, runs.end_time AS runs_end_time, 
runs.source_version AS runs_source_version, runs.lifecycle_stage AS runs_lifecycle_stage, runs.artifact_uri AS runs_artifact_uri, 
runs.experiment_id AS runs_experiment_id, CASE WHEN (runs.start_time IS NULL) THEN @P1 ELSE @P2 END AS anon_1 
FROM runs 
WHERE runs.experiment_id IN (N''0'') AND runs.lifecycle_stage IN (N''active'') 
ORDER BY CASE WHEN (runs.start_time IS NULL) THEN @P5 ELSE @P6 END, runs.start_time DESC, runs.run_uuid
 OFFSET 0 ROWS
 FETCH FIRST @P8 ROWS ONLY',1,0,N'0',N'active',1,0,0,100
 select @p1
```
One more observation, If I use same variable name for both the **case** statement, one in the **select** clause and other in the **order by** clause then things again work - 
```

declare @p1 int
set @p1=NULL
exec sp_prepexec @p1 output,N'@P1 int,@P2 int,@P3 nvarchar(2),@P4 nvarchar(12),@P5 int,@P6 int,@P7 int,@P8 int',
N'SELECT DISTINCT runs.run_uuid AS runs_run_uuid, runs.name AS runs_name, runs.source_type AS runs_source_type, 
runs.source_name AS runs_source_name, runs.entry_point_name AS runs_entry_point_name, runs.user_id AS runs_user_id, 
runs.status AS runs_status, runs.start_time AS runs_start_time, runs.end_time AS runs_end_time, 
runs.source_version AS runs_source_version, runs.lifecycle_stage AS runs_lifecycle_stage, runs.artifact_uri AS runs_artifact_uri, 
runs.experiment_id AS runs_experiment_id, CASE WHEN (runs.start_time IS NULL) THEN @P1 ELSE @P2 END AS anon_1 
FROM runs 
WHERE runs.experiment_id IN (N''0'') AND runs.lifecycle_stage IN (N''active'') 
ORDER BY CASE WHEN (runs.start_time IS NULL) THEN @P1 ELSE @P2 END, runs.start_time DESC, runs.run_uuid
 OFFSET 0 ROWS
 FETCH FIRST @P8 ROWS ONLY',1,0,N'0',N'active',1,0,0,100
 select @p1
```

+1 same issue as above, just explained a bit more:

When the values (1, 0) in the `CASE` statements are parameterized the query fails with:

```
ORDER BY items must appear in the select list if SELECT DISTINCT is specified.
```

SQL Server seems to not be able to check that the parameterized values in the `ORDER BY` clause are in fact in the `SELECT` clause.

```sql
-- [parameters: (1, 0, '0', 'active', 1, 0, 0, 100)]

DECLARE @p1 INT = 1
DECLARE @p2 INT = 0
DECLARE @p3 VARCHAR(10) = '0'
DECLARE @p4 VARCHAR(10) = 'active'
DECLARE @p5 INT = 1
DECLARE @p6 INT = 0
DECLARE @p7 INT = 0
DECLARE @p8 INT = 100

SELECT 
    DISTINCT runs.run_uuid AS runs_run_uuid,
    runs.name AS runs_name,
    runs.source_type AS runs_source_type,
    runs.source_name AS runs_source_name,
    runs.entry_point_name AS runs_entry_point_name,
    runs.user_id AS runs_user_id,
    runs.STATUS AS runs_status,
    runs.start_time AS runs_start_time,
    runs.end_time AS runs_end_time,
    runs.source_version AS runs_source_version,
    runs.lifecycle_stage AS runs_lifecycle_stage,
    runs.artifact_uri AS runs_artifact_uri,
    runs.experiment_id AS runs_experiment_id,
    CASE -- this CASE selects either 1 or 0 to the anon_1 field 
    WHEN (runs.start_time IS NULL)
        THEN @p1 -- 1
    ELSE @p2 -- 0
    END AS anon_1
FROM runs
WHERE
    runs.experiment_id IN (@p3)
    AND runs.lifecycle_stage IN (@p4)
ORDER BY
    -- this CASE orders by column index 1 or 0... is that even what we want? I don't think 0 is a valid column index...?
    CASE
    WHEN (runs.start_time IS NULL)
        THEN @p5 -- 1
    ELSE @p6 -- 0
    END,
    runs.start_time DESC,
    runs.run_uuid OFFSET @p7 ROWS

FETCH FIRST @p8 ROWS ONLY
```

I'm not sure how to make SQLAlchemy pass those values non-parameterized, or otherwise modify the source, so as a temp solution I'm just removing that first expression in the `ORDER BY` clause by changing this line:

https://github.com/mlflow/mlflow/blob/0fa849ad75e5733bf76cc14a4455657c5c32f107/mlflow/store/tracking/sqlalchemy_store.py#L795

to:
```py
    .order_by(*parsed_orderby[1:])
```

because I don't really care about the order here, and all my records have start_time anyways.

NOTE - The query also works as-is if `DISTINCT` is removed. Is `DISTINCT` necessary? Wouldn't all the runs have unique `uuid`s anyways?

+1 same issue here

Happens with mlflow v1.21.0, not prior.
Running Python 3.8.5 on CentOS7.
alembic version is 1.4.1, sqlalchemy is 1.4.29

The temporary solution with altering sqlalchemy_store.py works for me too.

Where exactly are those SQL statements generated?

Edit:
We have another instance running mlflow v1.13.1. Here the issue also appears, but not right away when the UI is loaded, but when the run list is sorted by any column.
+1 Can this issue be solved in `mlflow` ?
